text.p: These are some of the leading stories in the Jordanian press on Monday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.
JORDAN TIMES
- King Hussein, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's adviser discuss peace process, bilateral accords.
- King congratulates Saudi monarch.
AL-DUSTOUR
- Wide-ranging changes on list of custom tarrifs.
- Important speech for Prince Hassan expected on issue of refugees and UNRWA services at opening of emergency meeting of host and donor countries in Amman on Monday.
- Deputy Trad al-Qadi resigns from parliament saying lower house of parliament is a "game" and "serves certain groups".
- Energy minister says there are encouraging signs about the possibility of finding crude oil in Jordan.
- Kuwait's Awqaf minister to visit Jordan for the first time since 1990 Gulf crisis.
AL RAI
- Jordan to demand discussions on reducing UNRWA services during the extraordinary meeting on Monday.
- The lower house of parliament committee on "Palestine" condemn's Israel's settlement policies.
- Jordanian government follows with concern death of Jordanian citizen in Iraq.
- Saudi Arabia recruits 600 Jordanian women teachers.
AL-ASWAQ
- Jordan rejects widening of settlements in West Bank.
- No new taxes or fees in 1997 state budget.
- Agriculture minister says we have not allowed the private sector to import olive oil.
- New details on the killing of a Jordanian truck driver in Iraq. Jordan formally asks Iraq to investigate incident.
